00:00:01.040 --> 00:00:06.660
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:06.660 --> 00:00:10.270
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: Joy Harjo and A.B.
Spellman could not be better suited

00:00:10.270 --> 00:00:12.380
to be up here with me today.

00:00:12.380 --> 00:00:17.590
Both are claimed poets but both are
also uniquely connected to music.

00:00:17.590 --> 00:00:22.510
Joy Harjo performed for many years
with her band, Poetic Justice,

00:00:22.510 --> 00:00:25.360
and currently tours
with Aerodynamics.

00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:29.890
She has 5 CDs of music and poetry
including her most recent award

00:00:29.890 --> 00:00:35.210
winning album of traditional fruit,
Red Dreams, A Trail Beyond Tears

00:00:35.210 --> 00:00:37.290
and Winding Through the Milky Way,

00:00:37.290 --> 00:00:39.970
which won the Native
American music award

00:00:39.970 --> 00:00:44.220
for best female artist
of the year in 2009.

00:00:44.220 --> 00:00:47.240
Harjo currently has a commission
from the Public Theatre of New York

00:00:47.240 --> 00:00:52.390
to write, We Were There When
Jazz Was Invented, a musical play

00:00:52.390 --> 00:00:54.580
that will restore southeastern
natives

00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:58.950
to the American story
of blues and jazz.

00:00:58.950 --> 00:01:03.610
Speaking of jazz A.B. Spellman
is an expert in the form.

00:01:03.610 --> 00:01:07.280
He published his first book
of poems, The Beautiful Days,

00:01:07.280 --> 00:01:11.940
in 1964 by working as
a jazz music reviewer.

00:01:11.940 --> 00:01:16.620
In addition to writing reviews,
essays and poetry for Metronome,

00:01:16.620 --> 00:01:20.740
Down Beat and Rhythm Magazine,
he published Four Lives

00:01:20.740 --> 00:01:23.720
in the Bepop Business in 1966.

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:29.640 position:56%
In 1975, Spellman became director of
the Arts in Education Study Project

00:01:29.640 --> 00:01:34.250
for the National Endowment for the
Arts where he worked until 2005.

00:01:34.250 --> 00:01:38.360
His service to the organization is
honored by the A.B. Spellman Award

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:41.990
for Jazz Advocacy bestowed
upon an individual

00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:46.290
who has contributed significantly
to the appreciation, knowledge

00:01:46.290 --> 00:01:49.950
and advancement of
the art form of jazz.

00:01:49.950 --> 00:01:54.740
